<comment datatype='string'>Results suggest that the &lt;i&gt;dps&lt;/i&gt; promoter is recognized by both  the &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;70&lt;/sup&gt; holoenzyme and &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;S&lt;/sup&gt; holoenzyme, since OxyR acts on &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;70&lt;/sup&gt;, and in addition the starts of the OxyR-dependent and the &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;S&lt;/sup&gt;-dependent transcripts are identical.  This promoter displays an unusual form of regulation. If cells are treated with hydrogen peroxide during exponential growth, &lt;i&gt;dps&lt;/i&gt; transcription is induced by OxyR, which activates &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;70&lt;/sup&gt; RNA polymerase. Surprisingly, the same promoter is also  activated by IHF and &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;S&lt;/sup&gt; at the onset of the stationary phase. It is assumed that both OxyR and IHF bind upstream of the &lt;i&gt;dps&lt;/i&gt; promoter  and that the mechanisms of activation act independently of each other.  The promoter has a a sequence that conforms to the consensus -10, but no obvious -35 sequence is present. Possibly, the &lt;i&gt;dps&lt;/i&gt;  promoter is  not ideally bound by either holoenzyme, leading to the need for  IHF to enhance the binding of &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;S&lt;/sup&gt; RNA polymerase and of OxyR to enhance the binding  of &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;70&lt;/sup&gt; RNA polymerase. 
&lt;p&gt;
The &lt;i&gt;dpS&lt;/i&gt; gene is positively regulated by RpoS in stationary phase, and it is mainly controlled at the level of transcription [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11157932&quot;&gt;Phadtare01&lt;/a&gt;]. The effect by RpoS is likely indirect and might be mediated by an intermediate regulator that itself is directly regulated by RpoS.  Phadtare  et al. (2001) found that CspC and CspE upregulate the expression of &lt;i&gt;dps&lt;/i&gt; by regulating the expression of RpoS itself [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11157932&quot;&gt;Phadtare01&lt;/a&gt;]. 
&lt;p&gt;
Fis and H-NS control &amp;sigma; factor selection at the &lt;i&gt;dps&lt;/i&gt; promoter [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18452510&quot;&gt;Grainger08&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
This promoter appears to be activated during &amp;sigma;E induction. It is induced during the first 5 minutes following &amp;sigma;E induction, decreased from 5 to 10 minutes, induced from 10 to 15 minutes, and decreased from 15 to 20 minutes [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31992590&quot;&gt;Lacoux20&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;

</comment>
